This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

**Version Used**: 
.NET SDK 8.0.300

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Base class.
/// </summary>
public abstract class Base
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Gets the value.
    /// </summary>
    protected abstract string Value { get; }
}

/// <summary>
/// Derived class.
/// </summary>
public sealed class Derived : Base
{
    protected override string Value => throw new NotImplementedException();
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:

[`CS1591: Missing XML comment for publicly visible type or member Derived.Value`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1591)

**Expected Behavior**:

No warning

**Actual Behavior**:

Warning

**Additional Context**:

The above repro, where we are overriding a method, is the real-world scenario I am hitting.

However, the pathological case of non-virtual protected members in sealed types also returns the diagnostic, though this is bad code:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Derived class.
/// </summary>
public sealed class Derived
{
    protected string Value => throw new NotImplementedException();
}
```

**Version Used**: 17.10.0 Preview 6.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```C#
class Program
{
    class MyClass { }
    static void Main()
    {
        MyClass myClass;
        mycl|
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
`myClass` be preselected, it differs in only one letter casing. (I would also expect the first letter to be more important when ambiguous.)

**Actual Behavior**:
Once you type `c`, the preselection changes to `MyClass`, although it differs in two letters:
![image](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/assets/10546952/e6f0891d-b976-4d26-b096-a396c55362a1)
Even if the current scoring makes them equal, that should not be enough to change the existing preselection.

## Background and Motivation

https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/blob/main/proposals/ref-struct-interfaces.md

## Proposed API

```diff
namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Specifies capabilities that may or may not be supported by the common language runtime the compilation is
    /// targeting.
    /// </summary>
    public enum RuntimeCapability
    {
+       /// <summary>
+       /// Indicates that this version of runtime supports generic type parameters allowing substitution with a ref struct.
+       /// </summary>
+       ByRefLikeGenerics = 8,
    }
}
```
 The name of the new enum item matches the name of the field from BCL - `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RuntimeFeature.ByRefLikeGenerics` (see https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/blob/main/proposals/ref-struct-interfaces.md#representation-in-metadata).


```diff
namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Represents a type parameter in a generic type or generic method.
    /// </summary>
    /// <remarks>
    /// This interface is reserved for implementation by its associated APIs. We reserve the right to
    /// change it in the future.
    /// </remarks>
    public interface ITypeParameterSymbol : ITypeSymbol
    {
+       /// <summary>
+       /// True if the 'allows ref struct' constraint was specified for the type parameter.
+       /// </summary>
+       bool AllowsByRefLike { get; }
    }
}
```
The new property is named after a flag in BCL `System.Reflection.GenericParameterAttributes.AllowByRefLike` (see https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/blob/main/proposals/ref-struct-interfaces.md#representation-in-metadata).
